erives the surname Howell from Corn. -Brit, houl, the sun; and he adds, high, exalted.' But Hywel is rather from hywel, conspicuous."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Joyce","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Apparently from the Norman male name <i>Josce</i> (Middle English <i>Josse</i>), which in turn is from <i>Jodocus</i>, a Latinized form of a Breton name, <i>Iodoc</i>, meaning ‘lord’, borne by a 7th-century Breton saint. The name was in use in England among Breton followers of William the Conqueror. However, although this was fairly common as a male given name in the Middle Ages, it had virtually died out by the 14th century. There is evidence of its use as a girl's name from the 16th century onwards in parishes with strong Puritan links, which suggests that it may have been associated with the vocabulary word <i>joy</i>;  see  Joy .  It was strongly revived in the 19th century under the influence of popular fiction. It is borne by characters in Mrs  Henry Wood's  East Lynne (  1861 ) and  Edna Lyall's  In the Golden Days (  1885 ). Modern use may well have been influenced also by the common Irish surname derived from the medieval Norman male name.  See also  Joss ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Joyce Ferch Hywel was born about 1210, in Pen-y-Cae, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom, her father, Hywell Ap Maredudd, was 26 and her mother, Ann ferch Gwilym \"Gwyn\", was 22."},"et":{"Abt 1210–":"umbes 1210–Surnud","1140–Female":"1140–Surnud","1200–Female":"1200–Surnud","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","1231–Female":"1231–Surnud","1240–Female":"1240–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1196–1290":"1196–1290","1196–Male":"1196–Surnud","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","1247–1335":"1247–1335","1185–1246":"1185–1246","1190–Female":"1190–Surnud","1190":"1190","1231":"1231","1230":"1230","1185":"1185","1196":"1196","1240":"1240","1140":"1140","1290":"1290","Abt 1230":"umbes 123